                                                                                                               Tata Steel net halves
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Hard-hit                                  
	Calcutta, Oct. 27: Tata Steels second-quarter net profit has declined nearly 50 per cent on lower prices, while revenue has dropped 18 per cent.         
	The company, excluding the Corus operation of Europe, earned a net income of Rs 902.94 crore compared with Rs 1,787.81 crore in the same quarter last fiscal.        
	Total income declined to Rs 5,768.16 crore from Rs 7,054.33 crore in the corresponding period a year ago.         
	The company said the second quarter of the last fiscal, just preceding Lehman Brothers fall and the ensuing crisis in the global economy, was best in Tata Steels history in terms of profitability.         
	Steel prices reached the dizzy heights of Rs 40,000 a tonne in that quarter compared with Rs 29,000-30,000 a tonne now.        
	Tata Steel has recorded higher profits on a quarter-on-quarter basis in this fiscal. The company had posted a profit of Rs 789.8 crore in the first quarter.        
	The company also improved the EBIDTA (earning before interest, depreciation and tax) margin  an indicator of the profitability of its core operation  from 32 per cent in the first quarter to 35 per cent in the second quarter. The EBIDTA margin was soaring at 50 per cent in the second quarter of last fiscal.        
	Tata Steel India sold 1.46 million tonnes of steel in the country compared with 1.22 million tonnes in the same period last year.                                                                                                                                        
